Problem.Description: In the class, the teacher wants to split all students into groups of three. Let's assume that all students are numbered from 1 to n. Some of the student are friends, so that they want to be on the same group. The teacher wants the groups to show good results, so he wants the following condition to hold: if the i-th student and j-th students are friend, then the i-th and the j-th students must be on the same team. Also, it is obvious that each student must be on exactly one team. If A and B are friend, B and C are friend, so A and C are friend.
Problem.InputSpec: The first line of the input contains integers n and m (1 ≤ n ≤ 5000, 0 ≤ m ≤ 5000. Then follow m lines, each contains a pair of integers ai, bi (1 ≤ ai, bi ≤ n) the pair ai, bi means that students with numbers ai and bi are friend. It is guaranteed that each pair ai, bi occurs in the input at most once.
Problem.OutputSpec: If the required division into groups doesn't exist, print “No”. Otherwise, print “Yes”.
